The program is trying to access the fourth element of a list (index 3) whic
which has only three elements. In programming languages that use zero based
based indexing (like Tundra), indexes start from 0, so the third element wi
will have an index of 2 not 3. Therefore, we need to correct our chooseBest
chooseBest function as follows:

```Tundra
def chooseBest(scores) {
  return scores[2];
}

val row = {
  name: "Ada",
  scores: [7, 8, 9]
};

val best = chooseBest(row.scores);
print(best);
```
This program should now correctly print '9' which is the third element in r
row.scores list as per zero-based indexing.
